---

# General Principles

Always read every available Java submission before documenting.

Infer the final understanding from all accepted solutions.

Never duplicate Java code.

Never copy editorials.

Never explain code line-by-line.

Prefer:

- reasoning
- patterns
- decision making

over implementation.

---

# Documentation Levels

Maintain documentation at four levels.

## Level 1

Problem README

Purpose

Revise one specific interview problem.

Contains

- Problem Summary
- Constraints
- Brute Force
- Core Observation
- Thinking Process
- Why the approach works
- Pattern Recognition
- Pattern Recognition Clues
- Alternative Approaches
- Critical Implementation Details
- Edge Cases
- Common Mistakes
- Complexity
- Similar Problems
- One-line Takeaway
- Revision Checklist
- Revision History

Never include full code.

---

## Level 2

Topic README

Purpose

Revise an entire topic.

Maintain

- Topic Overview
- Core Concepts
- Frequently Used Patterns
- Decision Tree
- Common Tricks
- Common Mistakes
- Complexity Cheat Sheet
- Problems Covered
- Topic Takeaways

Do not repeat individual problem explanations.

---

## Level 3

PATTERNS.md

Purpose

Create a reusable pattern encyclopedia.

For every pattern maintain

# Pattern Name

## When to Think About It

## Core Idea

## Recognition Clues

## Common Variations

## Complexity

## Common Mistakes

## Related Problems

## Key Takeaways

If the pattern already exists,

append new insights instead of duplicating.

---

## Level 4

REVISION.md

Purpose

Track revision only.

Maintain

| Problem | Topic | Difficulty | Confidence | Last Revision | Next Revision | Revision Count |

Never explain solutions here.

Also maintain

Priority Revision

Weak Topics

Recently Revised

Never Revised

